sentence: U.S. stocks declined Tuesday, with another overnight drop for Chinese stocks and disappointing quarterly results this morning by the world's largest retailer upstaging more upbeat data for the U.S. housing market.
Nine of 10 industry sectors in the S&P 500 closed in the red today although shares of consumer discretionary stocks managed to hang on to a narrow gain.
The Shanghai China Composite Index slumped to a 6.15% decline overnight, fueling new worries over global growth.
In particular, those concerns weighed on both precious and base metals, with January 2016 copper falling falling nearly 2% and shares of mining companies in the S&P 500 dropping 0.7% as a group.
Dow component Walmart ( WMT ) blamed recent employee wage increases and a stronger dollar for a 15% drop in Q2 earnings compared with year-ago levels.
It also cut its Q3 and FY15 profit outlooks, driving shares of the mega-retailer to a 19-month low.
The Walmart results also eclipsed positive results from Home Depot ( HD ), another Dow component company, as well as by TJX Companies ( TJX ) and Dick's Sporting Goods ( DKS ).

Homebuilder stocks eked out gains today after the Commerce Department said U.S. housing starts rose 0.2% to a seasonally-adjusted annual rate of 1.206 million homes, beating expert opinion looking an annualized pace of 1.180 million new starts.
June activity also were revised upward to 1.204 million from the 1.174 million annual pace initially reported.

But while housing starts rose to a nearly eight-year high last month, the Commerce Department also reported the number of new building permits declined 16.3% from year-ago levels to an annualized pace of 1.119 million.
Over the past 3 months, however, housing permits were being pulled at a 1.337 million annualized pace, up from the 1.028 million rate reported in March.
Crude oil futures avoided today's rout for commodities, with the October contract settling 71 cents higher at $43.12 per barrel.
October natural gas futures fell 3 cents to $2.70 per 1 million BTU while December gold shed $1.50 to finish at $1,117.10 per ounce.

Here's where the U.S. markets stood at the end-of-day:

(+) OMER, Reports more positive data from Phase II testing of its prospective treatment for thrombotic microangiopathies, increasing mean platelet count by 47% and reducing red blood cell fragmentation by 86%.
(+) KIQ, Association of American Railroads approves commercial field testing of the company's new bottom-outlet valve design for rail tank cars carrying crude oil, ethanol and other petrochemicals.
(+) EVOK, FDA approves study of its EVK-001 drug candidate adding the effect of EVK-001 on children with diabetic gastroparesis, which keeps food in the stomach for a abnormally long time.
(-) ANFI, Cut to Market Perform from Outperform at BMO Capital Markets.
(-) ANW, Q2 EPS of $0.15 lags Street view by $0.12 per share.
Revenue declines 29.8% from year-ago levels to $1.21 billion, topping the Capital IQ consensus expecting $1.06 bln.
(-) AKER, Q2 net loss widens 415% from last year to $0.41 per share.
Revenue declines 29% from last year to $966,922, trailing single analyst estimate expecting $2.6 mln.
Also creates $864,000 allowance for receivable due June 30.
